UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: circumstances of making, representation reliability, objective assessment, hearsay admissibility, fabrication risk, Mason P, Ambrosoli

The rule attributed to Ambrosoli (as cited by Mason P at [28]) is that, for the purposes of Evidence Act s 65, the court''s focus should be on the reliability of the prior representation itself rather than directly on the asserted fact to which the representation relates. This principle means that admissibility under s 65(2)(b) or (c) requires an objective inquiry into the circumstances in which the representation was made — for example, timing relative to the events ("shortly after"), specificity and contemporaneity of detail, absence of motive to fabricate, and surrounding conduct or statements of the maker — rather than an assessment that the substantive facts asserted are proven by independent corroboration. The source material indicates Ambrosoli was relied upon to support the proposition that the enquiry is concerned with the circumstances that warrant treating the representation as reliable notwithstanding its hearsay character. Because the original source text did not supply a full case citation for Ambrosoli, this chunk is marked [REVIEW]; the incomplete citation prevents providing standard case metadata (full citation and year). To apply the Ambrosoli principle in practice, practitioners should (a) identify precisely the representation to be tendered, (b) present evidence of the objective circumstances surrounding its making, and (c) resist conflating probative corroboration of the asserted fact with the separate statutory inquiry into the representation''s intrinsic reliability under s 65.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-authority---ambrosoli-mason-p-at-28-review';
