UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: tendency evidence, particular state of mind, propensity, relevance for inference, conforming behaviour, probative purpose, Evidence Act s97, admissibility test

Tendency evidence under Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 97 is evidence adduced to prove that a person had a tendency to act in a particular way or to have a particular state of mind, and is used to support an inference that the person acted in that way (or had that state of mind) on a particular occasion relevant to the proceeding. The critical feature of tendency evidence is its inferential purpose: evidence of past conduct or propensity is tendered not merely for its own sake but to make it more probable that the person acted similarly on the occasion in issue. Tendency evidence therefore requires careful analysis of relevance and probative utility and attracts the statutory controls in ss 95–101. A party seeking to avoid the application of s 97 cannot simply assert an alternative purpose; they must demonstrate that the evidence is relevant to a fact in issue by reasoning that does not involve drawing an inference from tendency to conforming behaviour.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 97 [2]';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: coincidence evidence, related events, significant probative value, similarity, improbability of coincidence, Evidence Act s98, admissibility threshold, rational effect on probability

Coincidence or "related events" evidence under Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 98 concerns two or more events alleged to be connected and admissible to show that, because of similarities, it is improbable they occurred coincidentally; such evidence may be adduced to prove that the accused did a specified act or had a specified state of mind that is a fact in issue. Section 98 requires that, having regard to similarities in the events and circumstances, the evidence have significant probative value: similarity is the central factor from which probative force is derived. If events are not sufficiently similar to make coincidence improbable, s 98 will not admit them for coincidence purposes. If evidence does not meet s 98, it may nevertheless be excluded under Evidence Act s 137 because its probative value is outweighed by unfair prejudice.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 98';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: coincidence test, four-step test, similarity assessment, significant probative value, balancing prejudice, juror assessment, related events

CGL v DPP (Vic) [2010] sets out a practical four-step framework for assessing admissibility of coincidence/related-events evidence: (1) Are the similarities in the specified events and their circumstances such that it is improbable the events occurred coincidentally? (2) If yes, would evidence of those events tend to prove that the accused did the specified act or had the specified state of mind that is a fact in issue? (3) If yes, does the evidence have significant probative value, either alone or having regard to other evidence the prosecution has adduced or will adduce? (4) If yes, does the probative value substantially outweigh any prejudicial effect on the accused? This framework operationalises the statutory s 98 requirement that similarity produce significant probative value and the s 101/s 137 balancing against prejudice.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-cgl-v-dpp-vic-2010-four-step-admissibility-test-for-coincidence-evidence-authori';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: R v PWD, tendency evidence, similarity not necessary to be striking, particular state of mind, violence, control, detaining, probative use

R v PWD, as cited in the source, confirms that for admissibility under s 97 it is not necessary that similar conduct be strikingly similar or closely similar; the authorities allow a range of similarities to support a tendency inference. The case emphasises that tendency evidence is adduced to render more probable an inference that the person acted in a particular way on the occasion in issue and that tendency need not show commission of the same crime on other occasions — it may show a general tendency (for example, to use violence or to control a partner) that is probative of whether the accused detained or acted in a particular way on the night in question.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-r-v-pwd-similarity-and-tendencycoincidence-authority';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: s95, hearsay exceptions, character evidence, re-purposing evidence, tendency use, coincidence use, admissibility precondition

Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 95 establishes that evidence admitted for one purpose (for example, admissible under a hearsay or character exception) cannot automatically be re‑used for tendency or coincidence purposes: if a party seeks to rely on that evidence as tendency or related-events evidence, the statutory requirements of s 97 or s 98 must still be satisfied. In short, admission under one head of admissibility does not waive the separate threshold and balancing exercises required for tendency or coincidence evidence; the prosecution cannot simply re-label admitted material as related-events evidence without satisfying the s 97/98 criteria.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 95';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: s101, prosecution evidence limits, substantial outweighing, prejudicial effect, opening the door, notice requirement, fairness, significant probative value

Section 101 of the Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) imposes additional limits when the prosecution seeks to adduce tendency or coincidence evidence against an accused: under s 101(2) the probative value of such evidence must substantially outweigh any prejudicial effect on the accused; ss 101(3)–(4) create exceptions where the accused "opens the door" by adducing relevant matter; and the section works with the notice and procedural requirements in ss 97–100. These provisions reflect heightened protection for accused persons when propensity-type material is led by the Crown and require careful judicial balancing of probative value against risk of unfair prejudice.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 101 [3]';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: s100, limiting direction, jury directions, evidence use limitation, judicial control, trial fairness, trial judge

Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 100 empowers the trial judge to give directions concerning the use of tendency or coincidence evidence, including limiting instructions and explanations of the proper inferential use of the material. A judicial direction may mitigate the prejudicial effect of propensity material and is a recognised exception/control mechanism rather than a standalone basis to admit otherwise inadmissible evidence.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 100';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: rebuttal, s97(2)(b), responding propensity evidence, probative relevance, evidence of tendency, defensive use

Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 97(2)(b) provides that tendency evidence may be adduced to rebut tendency evidence put forward by another party; in that limited context evidence of a tendency may be admissible not to prove the accused''s propensity generally but to meet an opposing party''s case about tendency. This is a targeted exception to the general restrictiveness of s 97 and requires that the rebuttal purpose be genuine and proportionate.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 97(2)(b)';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: s98 capacity, significant degree, rational effect on probability, hypothetical jury, admissibility, related events

DSJ v The Queen (as cited) holds that s 98 asks whether the evidence is capable, to a significant degree, of rationally affecting the assessment (ultimately by a jury) of the probability of the existence of a fact in issue. The case emphasises a realistic judicial assessment of the evidence'' capacity: if a hypothetical jury would likely regard the evidence as unimportant to the facts in issue, a trial judge may readily conclude the evidence lacks the required capacity for admissibility under s 98.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-dsj-v-the-queen-s-98-capacity-test-authority';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: s137, unfair prejudice, exclude evidence, related events, balancing test, criminal proceedings

W v The Queen (as cited) illustrates that if evidence does not qualify as a "related event" under s 98, its admissibility must still be tested under Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 137; the court must refuse admission of evidence adduced by the prosecutor if its probative value is outweighed by the danger of unfair prejudice. Thus failure to meet s 98 does not automatically permit admission — the s 137 exclusion remains available to exclude prejudicial material.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-w-v-the-queen-interplay-with-evidence-act-s-137-authority';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: Lockyer, relevance threshold, more than mere relevance, degree of consequence, admissibility standard, propensity material

Lockyer, as cited in the source notes, articulates that admissibility of tendency/related-events evidence requires "something more than mere relevance, but less than a substantial degree of relevance" — the evidence must also be important or of consequence. This formulation situates the threshold between trivial relevance and full proof of the disputed issue and supports the statutory requirement that probative value be significant.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-lockyer-relevance-threshold-for-tendencycoincedence-evidence-case-note';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: Jacara, Townsend, citation noted, authority cited, case law reference, [REVIEW]

]

The source cites Jacara v Perpetual Trustees and Townsend v Townsend in relation to tendency/coincedence jurisprudence but provides no substantive text or holdings. These cases were referenced by the author as relevant authorities; the source does not record the legal proposition attributed to them. This chunk flags the presence of those citations in the source for retrieval purposes and notes that the extract lacks specific doctrinal content from those decisions. [REVIEW]', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-case-references-with-limited-detail-jacara-v-perpetual-trustees-townsend-v-towns';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: s137, unfair prejudice, probative value, exclude evidence, balancing test, criminal proceedings

Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 137 requires that a court refuse to admit prosecution evidence if its probative value is outweighed by the danger of unfair prejudice to the defendant. This statutory exclusion often operates where tendency or related-events evidence fails the s 98 threshold or where significant prejudicial risk remains despite probative value. Judicial considerations under s 137 may include risk of jury misuse, emotional impact, and potential for distraction from core issues.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 137';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: notice requirement, pre-trial disclosure, s97 notice, s98 related events, s100 directions, defendant rights, procedural fairness

The Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) requires parties to give reasonable notice to other parties when seeking to adduce tendency or coincidence evidence (ss 97–100). These procedural rules ensure fairness and permit opposing parties and the court to assess admissibility in advance, consider limiting directions, and prepare responses. The notice requirements are integral to the protective regime surrounding propensity-type material, especially where the prosecution leads such evidence.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) ss 97–100';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: s79, expert evidence, underlying facts, admissibility conditions, probative value, qualifications, Langford v Tasmania, weight vs admissibility

Section 79 of the Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) governs expert opinion evidence: an expert may give an opinion within their specialised field, and such opinion is admissible if relevant and satisfies the conditions of s 79. Importantly, the source records (with authority in Langford v Tasmania [2018] TASCCA 1) that proof of the underlying facts and assumptions upon which an expert forms an opinion is not a necessary precondition of admissibility — failure to prove those factual assumptions affects weight, not admissibility, unless in extreme cases where the opinion is wholly speculative or irrelevant. The expert''s qualifications and the logical basis for the opinion remain critical to admissibility and weight.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 79';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: Langford v Tasmania, s79, underlying facts, admissibility vs weight, expert qualifications, IMM citation, probative weight

Langford v Tasmania [2018] TASCCA 1 holds that an expert''s opinion may be admissible even if some of the factual assumptions underlying the opinion are not independently proved; the absence of proof affects the weight the tribunal may give the opinion but does not ordinarily affect admissibility under s 79. The Court observed that provided the opinion is relevant and satisfies s 79 conditions, lack of proof for underlying assumptions generally goes to weight, not admissibility, except in extreme cases where the logical foundation is absent.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-langford-v-tasmania-2018-tascca-1-underlying-facts-and-weight-authority';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: s78, lay opinion, perception, admissible description, non-expert opinion, witness perceptions, descriptive weight

Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 78 permits a lay witness to give opinion evidence that is based on their perceptions and helps describe what they saw, heard, or otherwise perceived; such opinions are admissible to improve the descriptive weight of their testimony. Lay opinion under s 78 is not treated as previous representation or hearsay when expressing how the witness perceived events, but the court must ensure the opinion assists the fact-finder and does not usurp the role of expert evidence.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 78';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: expert qualifications, police expert, forensic ID, training & experience, exhibit identification, admissibility, s79 procedure, courtroom examination

To qualify a forensic or police officer as an expert under s 79, the proponent should elicit a concise statement of the witness''s specialised training and experience (years on the job, specialist roles or secondments, courses, internal training, forensic liaison, rank, and frequency of relevant incidents). The first sentence states the rule: a witness is qualified as an expert if the court is satisfied they possess specialised knowledge based on training, study or experience relevant to the opinion. The examiner should obtain confirmation that the witness has examined the specific exhibit, invite the witness to state their opinion about the exhibit, and lay out the factual and methodological basis for that opinion. These steps support admissibility and make the expert''s basis transparent for assessment of weight.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-practical-guidance-qualifying-an-expert-policedrug-identification-brent';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: police evidence, common practices, drug communications, devices, scales, clipseal bags, non-expert observations, contextual evidence

Police officers may give admissible non‑expert evidence about observations from numerous investigations, such as common forms of communication, devices, packaging, and behaviours in drug markets (for example, multiple mobile phones, encrypted devices, clipseal bags, scales). Such evidence is admissible as non‑expert contextual evidence describing what the witness has personally observed in their professional experience, provided it is presented as observation and not as an asserted fact requiring specialised opinion beyond their perception.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-nonexpert-police-evidence-about-drug-markets-and-communications';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: expert reports, not prior representation, drug analysis, cutting agents, common usage, valuation evidence, organisational knowledge, admissible content

Jackson v The State of Western Australia [2025] WASCA 33 (cited in the source) approves that an expert report is not evidence of a prior representation made by a person and cannot be used to prove the existence of a fact asserted in the report as a previous representation; rather, reports are admissible as the foundation for an expert''s opinion. The source records examples of permissible expert evidence approved in Jackson: evidence about cutting agents in methylamphetamine, methods of consumption and slang, market value and pandemic price effects, common possession items of street-level dealers, and organisational structure of dealing networks. These topics were treated as within the competence of policing experts and as relevant contextual material.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-expert-reports-and-jackson-v-the-state-of-western-australia-2025-wasca-33-author';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: video link, exhibit ID, witness copy, barcode, report confirmation, remote evidence, authentication, FFST confirmation

When a witness gives evidence via video link and a document or exhibit must be identified, the first sentence states the rule: the witness should confirm their identity, qualifications, and authorship of any report, state whether they possess a copy, and be permitted to refer to the document to identify sample ID details (such as sample identifier, barcode, and document identifiers). Once identification is given, the information should be confirmed against forensic/file system trial (FFST) records and the laboratory analysis result disclosed. These steps authenticate the exhibit for reception in court and permit the tribunal to assess chain of custody and reliability at a distance.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-procedure-for-identifying-documents-over-video-link-practical-rule';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: s43, witness refusal, oath refusal, committal warrant, imprisonment, compel testimony, magistrates'' power, seven days

Justices Act 1959 (Tas) s 43 provides that if a person summoned or brought before justices refuses to be examined on oath, refuses to take an oath, or having taken an oath refuses to answer questions without sufficient excuse, a justice with jurisdiction may commit the person to gaol for up to seven days by warrant unless the person then consents to be examined and answer. The provision is a statutory compulsion tool for magistrates'' courts and is procedural in nature; it permits temporary imprisonment to compel testimony where appropriate.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Justices Act 1959 (Tas) s 43';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: credibility, leading questions, partisan witness, "mere echo of counsel", cross-examination, defence favourable witness

Police v Endlay [2020] TASMC 13 demonstrates that a witness who functions as a partisan or defence‑favourable witness — answering entirely leading questions and acting as "a mere echo of counsel" — may attract judicial findings that the court places no weight on answers elicited in that manner. The decision illustrates the court''s approach to assessing credibility where the form of cross-examination and the role the witness plays affects the weight of their testimony.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-credibility-and-leading-cross-examination-police-v-endlay-2020-tasmc-13-authorit';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: complainant credibility, narrative detail, contemporaneous conduct, reporting, Kilby, corroborative behaviour, prompt complaint

Complainant credibility may be supported by a confidently narrated, chronological account populated by minor detail and by contemporaneous conduct consistent with the complaint — for example, immediate contact with friends or family and prompt reporting to police. Kilby [1973] HCA 30 is cited in the source for the proposition that such prompt and consistent actions are matters indicating credibility and that such behaviour may be a legitimate factor for the court to consider in assessing the truth of the complainant''s account.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-complainant-credibility-factors-narrative-coherence-contemporaneous-conduct-and-';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: s106, rebuttal, inconsistent statements, tender through other witnesses, s60 hearsay gateway, prior representation, impeachment

Section 106 of the Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) deals with rebuttal evidence and permits the tendering of other persons'' evidence to rebut or explain matters raised by a witness; where a witness'' evidence invites the use of rebuttal material, that material can be adduced through other witnesses. The source discusses that when a witness is asked about a prior representation and answers "could not remember", s 106 may be enlivened permitting the officer who took the earlier statement to be called to prove the prior representation — and, through the s 60/106 interaction, the prior representation may be admitted as proof of the fact if it meets the statutory gateways.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 106';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: rebuttal, direct evidence, coaching allegations, impeachment, s106 use, witness coaching

Australian Automotive Repairers Association v Insurance Australia Ltd (2006) FCAFC 33 is cited for the proposition that evidence sought to rebut a witness''s testimony can take the form of direct evidence (for example, witnesses who saw the primary witness being coached pre-trial); such direct rebuttal evidence can be admissible to rebut the witness''s account and operates within the framework of rebuttal/impeachment rules.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-australian-automotive-repairers-association-v-insurance-australia-ltd-2006-fcafc';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: refreshing memory, diary entries, previous representation, second-hand hearsay, s48, s43, s60, s106, admissibility

Neill‑Fraser v Tasmania (No 2) [2019] TASSC 11 deals with a witness who, having initially told police dates after consulting her diary, could not later find the diary and could not recall the dates at trial. The court allowed evidence that the witness had given the dates to police (through the interviewing officer) and held it was not inadmissible "second‑hand" hearsay because the witness''s representation was rooted in her contemporaneous personal notes (her diary) and therefore not reliant upon another person''s representation. The decision also illustrates the operation of s 43, s 48, s 60 and s 106 in refreshing memory and admitting prior representations for impeachment and substantive proof depending on circumstances.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-neill-fraser-v-tasmania-no-2-2019-tassc-11-diary-refreshment-and-secondhand-hear';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: s34, prosecution witness, informant anonymity, source privilege, drug prosecutions, statutory exemption

Misuse of Drugs Act 2001 (Tas) s 34 provides that a witness for the prosecution in proceedings under that Act is not obliged to disclose the fact of receiving information, the nature of that information, or the name of the person who provided the information. The provision creates a statutory non‑disclosure protection specific to prosecutions under the Misuse of Drugs Act, reflecting policy concerns about informant confidentiality in drug enforcement contexts.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Misuse of Drugs Act 2001 (Tas) s 34';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: s26, s192, control of questioning, production of documents, order of questioning, leave on terms, curtailing cross-examination, trial efficiency, fairness

Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) s 26 gives the court broad control over the manner of witness questioning, the production and use of documents, order of questioning, and the presence or behaviour of persons related to questioning; s 192 permits the court to grant leave, permission or direction on any terms it thinks fit and requires the court to consider factors like the length of the hearing, unfairness to parties or witnesses, importance of the evidence, and the nature of the proceeding. The source records Police v Endlay [2020] TASMC 13 as an example where s 26 and the s 192 factors were relied upon to disallow particular forms of questioning and to ensure a fair and efficient hearing.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Evidence Act 2001 (Tas) ss 26, 192';
