UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: compensation orders, summary procedure, s68(6), evidence suffices, civil damages on account, not for complex claims, Town or Magistrates’ Court practice

Lusted v Doornbusch [2011] TASMC 28 explains that straightforward compensation orders can be granted on the spot in summary proceedings. The legislation''s purpose is to provide a summary and inexpensive method to compensate victims for personal injury or property damage; it is not intended for complicated claims that require extensive investigation. Under s68(6) (as applied in the decision), a court may make a compensation order if the facts sufficiently appear from evidence presented at trial, available documents, or admissions. An award is in the nature of an account of civil damages and the court should decline to make orders where there is a real issue requiring civil proceedings.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Criminal Code s255A';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: facts for prosecutor, sentencing evidence, Evidence Act s4(2), Sentencing Act s81, Parker v Tasmania, informal evidence, proof standard

Facts relied upon by the prosecution to support sentencing must be proved by evidence; they may be presented formally or informally. Evidence can be submitted under Evidence Act s4(2) (formal evidence) or informally under Sentencing Act s81; in Tasmania it is common to submit facts informally at sentencing, as explained in Parker v Tasmania [2019] TASCCA 16 at [28]. The sentencing court will assess the reliability and weight of the evidence when determining aggravating circumstances.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-authority---attorney-general-for-tasmania-v-b-2010-tascca-6';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: De Simoni, sentencing limits, uncharged conduct, aggravating facts, not punishable if constitute different offence, Tasmania application, Walsh, Lovegrove

The De Simoni principle (The Queen v De Simoni (1980) 147 CLR 383) provides that a person may only be punished for the offence of which they have been convicted and a sentencing judge cannot take into account circumstances of aggravation that would have warranted conviction for a more serious offence with different elements. The principle applies to Tasmania as reflected in Tasmania v Gladwin [2016] TASSC 64 and earlier authorities (Walsh v The Queen [1996] TASSC 55; Lovegrove v The Queen [1961]). While a sentencing judge may consider all conduct of the accused, they must not impose punishment for an offence they were not charged with or convicted of.', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Sentencing Act s94';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: De Simoni principle, sentencing boundaries, uncharged conduct, High Court authority

