UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: magistrate jurisdiction, s308, remittal order, s27(4A), resentencing, efficiency, adjourn to Supreme Court, practitioner advice

What this chunk covers: Practitioner commentary on whether a Magistrate can deal with breach of suspended sentence imposed by Supreme Court and suggested practical approaches.
"Neither I, or they, are aware of any case precedent in relation to this issue.  As far as my view goes, s 308 does not apply to this situation.  If a remittal order is made under s 308 it gives the Magistrate the powers of a trial judge but is limited solely to that situation.

 

As a starting point, a Magistrate does not have the jurisdiction to sentence for an Indictable crime.  Just like a Judge only has jurisdiction to sentence for a summary offence via s 385A of the Code or if someone is found guilty of an alternative offence (such as possession in a trafficking case).  That means, that on its face, HH McKee would not have jurisdiction to resentence for the Code assault.  However, I would argue that s 27(4A) gives him that power.  The legislative intent of that sub section seems to be to ensure that other Courts can deal with breach applications if they are sentencing for the offences/crimes that breach it.  That is to ensure efficiency in the process and to allow a sentencing judicial officer to properly consider principles like totality etc.  Judges often sentence on breaches of CPS suspended sentences whilst sentencing for the breaching crime, even though normally they wouldn''t have jurisdiction to deal with the matter.  That is because s 27(4A) gives them the power to hear and determine the application and hence, arguably utilise any of the options in s 27(4C), including resentencing for a crime they would not normally have jurisdiction to sentence on.

 

Anyway, that is my view.  If Magistrate McKee however is not with you on that, and is not convinced that he should simply activate all of the sentence, then it may be safer for him to simply adjourn the breach application for the Supreme Court to deal with."

---', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'secondary-practitioner-note-magistrate-jurisdiction-s-308-s-274a-and-remittaladjournment-o';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: unjust, s27(4C), Tanner v Brown, factors, activation presumption, suspended sentences, public policy

What this chunk covers: Judicial exposition on the meaning of "unjust" for the purposes of s 27(4C) and factors to consider.
### Meaning of Unjust

*Biddle v Hayward \[2014\] TASSC 65*

**The meaning of the term "unjust" in [[s 27(4C)]{.underline}](http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/consol_act/rsada1970264/s27.html)**

2.  The term "unjust" in the Act is not defined. It has largely been left to individual judicial officers to determine what is and what is not unjust in particular cases. However, there has been guidance in the form of an analysis of the provision by Wood J in *Tanner v Brown* [[\[2011\] TASSC 59]{.underline}](http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/tas/TASSC/2011/59.html) at [[\[84\]]{.underline}](http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/tas/TASSC/2011/59.html#para84) to \[99\]. With respect, I adopt her Honour''s analysis as did Pearce J in *Cannell v Hughes* [[\[2014\] TASSC 41.]{.underline}](http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/tas/TASSC/2014/41.html) At [[\[14\]]{.underline}](http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/tas/TASSC/2014/41.html#para14), his Honour said:

" The operation of [[s27]{.underline}](http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/consol_act/rsada1970264/s27.html) was considered by Wood J in *Tanner v Brown* (above). I would respectfully adopt her Honour''s analysis. There is no need to repeat all of it, although I will refer to some parts of it. Her Honour''s decision was followed by Crawford CJ in *Jones v Clarke* [[\[2012\] TASSC 21]{.underline}](http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/tas/TASSC/2012/21.html), and has been considered in other cases including by Porter J in *Chatwin v Godfrey* [[\[2013\] TASSC 70.]{.underline}](http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/tas/TASSC/2013/70.html) Introduction of [[s27]{.underline}](http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/consol_act/rsada1970264/s27.html) on 1 January 2011 was intended to result in a hardening of the approach to suspended sentences. **It has long been the case that, generally speaking, if an offender wastes an opportunity offered by the court by re-offending, then a suspended sentence should be activated. Ordinarily, suspended sentences are meant to be a last chance**. Any unjustified departure from that principle undermines the integrity of the system of suspended sentences and the extent to which they may deter future offenders. As Wood J pointed out in *Tanner v Brown* at \[91\], [[s27]{.underline}](http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/consol_act/rsada1970264/s27.html) now enshrines that policy in a legislative form and creates a presumption that the suspended sentence will be activated unless the court is of the opinion that it is unjust. **The clear starting point is that the sentence should be activated.** The court is not considering the original sentence afresh but determining whether activation of the sentence is unjust. In the words used by Wood J in *Tanner v Brown* (above) at \[103\], ''the exercise of the sentencing function is not at large, and is limited to an evaluation of whether it would be unjust to activate the sentence''. In considering an application under [[s27]{.underline}](http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/consol_act/rsada1970264/s27.html) there may be sentencing considerations which properly incline a sentencing court against activation of a suspended sentence, but which fall short of justifying a conclusion that it would be unjust to do so. The meaning of ''unjust'' is not prescribed by the [*[Sentencing Act]{.underline}*](http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/consol_act/sa1997121/). Its ordinary meaning, according to the Macquarie Dictionary online, is ''not in accordance with justice or fairness''. It is for the sentencing court to consider and weigh the circumstances of each case. In the circumstances of this case, the most important factors seem to me to be:

- [the nature and circumstances of the offences for which the sentence was originally imposed;]{.mark}

- [the nature and gravity of the breach in comparison to the original offences and whether activation of the suspended sentence may represent a disproportionate response;]{.mark}

- [the lapse of time between the imposition of the suspended sentence and the breach;]{.mark}

- [whether there is any, and if so what, indication of reform and rehabilitation. That is, whether the suspended sentence may be having its desired effect."]

---', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Biddle v Hayward [2014] TASSC 65 - Meaning of ''unjust'' in s 27(4C)';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: disparity, breach, suspended sentence, Chatwin v Godfrey, statutory condition

What this chunk covers: Judicial note on the significance of disparity between original offending and breaching offending.
### Disparity between offences

*Chatwin v Godfrey \[2013\] TASSC 70*

11 The disparity in nature between original offending and breaching offending is a factor, but I do not regard it as one of great significance in general terms. The condition that no offence punishable by imprisonment be committed during a specified period is a statutory condition of suspending the execution of the term of imprisonment. Parliament''s intention was plain enough. The object is to punish, as well as to rehabilitate, and the rehabilitative aspect is directed towards people becoming law abiding citizens, not selective offenders.

---', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Chatwin v Godfrey [2013] TASSC 70 - disparity between original and breaching offending';
UPDATE secondary_sources SET enriched_text = 'Concepts: youth offenders, public interest, activation, Allie v Wilkie, Smith''s Case, rehabilitation priority

What this chunk covers: Judicial considerations about public interest and young offenders when deciding activation of suspended sentences.
**Allie v Wilkie \[2019\] TASSC 27 (28 June 2019)**

In terms of the public interest, the following passage from the Court of Criminal Appeal in England in *Smith''s Case *[\[1964\] Crim LR 70](http://www.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/LawCite?cit=%5b1964%5d%20Crim%20LR%2070),* *endorsed by Nettlefold J in *Gray v Strickland *A44/1978,* *approved by the Court of Criminal Appeal, see *DPP v R,K D* [\[2018\] TASCCA 10](http://www.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/viewdoc/au/cases/tas/TASCCA/2018/10.html) at [\[37\]](http://www.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/viewdoc/au/cases/tas/TASCCA/2018/10.html#para37), has particular application.

*"In the case of a young offender there can hardly ever be any conflict between the public interest and that of the offender. The public have no greater interest than that he should become a good citizen. The difficult task of the court is to determine what treatment gives the best chance of realising that object. That realisation is the first and by far the most important consideration."*

*KL\*

---', enriched = 1 WHERE id = 'Allie v Wilkie [2019] TASSC 27 - activation and public interest for young offenders';
